3. Detailed Findings & Remediation
3.1 Safeguard Data Privacy — Rating: RED

Finding A: Data in Transit — ALREADY RESOLVED
Native Network Encryption is confirmed active. No further action required for this finding.

Finding B: RMAN Backups Unencrypted — FIXABLE (Native, No License Required)
All RMAN backup pieces are currently unencrypted. Password-based RMAN backup encryption is available in Oracle 19c at no additional cost and does NOT require the Advanced Security Option (TDE wallet-based encryption does require ASO, but password-based does not).

✓	Enable RMAN password-based backup encryption:
◦	RMAN> CONFIGURE ENCRYPTION FOR DATABASE ON;
◦	RMAN> SET ENCRYPTION ON IDENTIFIED BY 'YourStrongPassphrase' ONLY;
◦	Use ONLY keyword to enforce password-based encryption (no wallet required).
◦	Store the encryption passphrase securely in your password vault. Without it, backups CANNOT be restored.
◦	Verify: RMAN> LIST BACKUP; -- encrypted column should show 'YES'
✓	Configure encryption for all future RMAN jobs:
◦	RMAN> CONFIGURE ENCRYPTION ALGORITHM 'AES256';
◦	AES256 is the strongest available and has no performance impact on modern hardware.
✓	For existing unencrypted backups: re-take a full backup with encryption enabled. Old unencrypted backups should be expired and deleted per retention policy once the new encrypted set is validated.

Finding C: Data at Rest Unencrypted (Tablespaces/Columns) — NO NATIVE FIX
NO FREE FIX AVAILABLE: Transparent Data Encryption (TDE) and column-level encryption require Oracle Advanced Security Option (ASO), which is a paid add-on to Enterprise Edition. There is no native Oracle 19c EE mechanism to encrypt tablespaces or columns without ASO.
⚠	This risk cannot be technically remediated without purchasing the Advanced Security Option.
⚠	Recommended action: Formally document this as an accepted residual risk in your security risk register. Include: risk owner, business justification for non-remediation, compensating controls (access restriction, auditing, physical security), and planned review date.
⚠	Compensating controls to partially reduce exposure (implement these regardless):
◦	Restrict OS-level access to Oracle datafile directories via Unix file permissions (chmod 600 on datafiles, owned by oracle:dba).
◦	Ensure ASM disk groups are not directly accessible to non-oracle OS accounts.
◦	Confirm NNE is enforced so data cannot be intercepted in transit (already done).
◦	Audit all SELECT operations on tables known to contain PII/PHI (see Section 3.5).
 
3.2 Control Access to Data — Rating: RED

Finding A: DBAs Have Access to PII/PHI — PARTIAL FIX via VPD
Oracle Virtual Private Database (VPD), also known as Fine-Grained Access Control (FGAC), is included with Oracle Enterprise Edition at no extra cost. It allows row- and column-level security policies that can restrict DBA-level accounts from seeing sensitive data values (they see NULLs or masked output instead of real values).

✓	Identify tables containing PII/PHI (cross-reference DBSAT Discoverer output or known application schema).
✓	Create a VPD security policy function for each sensitive table:
◦	CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION restrict_pii(schema IN VARCHAR2, tname IN VARCHAR2)
◦	  RETURN VARCHAR2 AS BEGIN
◦	  IF SYS_CONTEXT('USERENV','SESSION_USER') IN ('DBA_USER1','SYS','SYSTEM') THEN
◦	    RETURN '1=0';  -- returns no rows for DBAs
◦	  END IF; RETURN NULL; END;
◦	/
◦	EXEC DBMS_RLS.ADD_POLICY('HR','EMPLOYEES','RESTRICT_DBA_ACCESS',
◦	  'HR','RESTRICT_PII', 'SELECT,UPDATE,DELETE', TRUE, TRUE);
◦	Adapt the function logic to your specific access control requirements (role-based, time-based, etc.).
◦	VPD policies survive DBA SELECT * attempts — the WHERE clause is injected at parse time.
◦	Note: VPD does not protect against users with EXEMPT ACCESS POLICY privilege. Audit who holds this privilege.
✓	Audit who has EXEMPT ACCESS POLICY:
◦	SELECT grantee FROM dba_sys_privs WHERE privilege = 'EXEMPT ACCESS POLICY';

RESIDUAL RISK: VPD restricts data visibility via SQL but does not prevent OS-level file access or DBA use of data export utilities when granted DATAPUMP_EXP_FULL_DATABASE. Compensate by auditing Data Pump exports and restricting OS datafile access (see 3.1).

Finding B: PII/PHI in Sub-Production Environments — PARTIAL FIX (Manual Scripts)
Oracle Data Masking Pack (DMS) is not available without purchase. However, masking can be performed manually using custom PL/SQL scripts. This requires more effort but achieves the same outcome.
✓	After each sub-prod refresh, run a masking script. Example for common PII fields:
◦	BEGIN
◦	  UPDATE hr.employees SET
◦	    first_name   = DBMS_RANDOM.STRING('U', 6),
◦	    last_name    = DBMS_RANDOM.STRING('U', 8),
◦	    email        = DBMS_RANDOM.STRING('L', 6) || '@test.invalid',
◦	    phone_number = '555-' || LPAD(TRUNC(DBMS_RANDOM.VALUE(1000,9999)),4,'0'),
◦	    salary       = ROUND(DBMS_RANDOM.VALUE(30000, 120000), -3);
◦	  COMMIT;
◦	END;
◦	/
◦	Extend this pattern to all tables identified as containing PII/PHI.
◦	Use DBMS_CRYPTO for format-preserving masking of SSNs, card numbers, etc. where referential integrity must be maintained.
✓	Build a masking runbook listing every table/column containing PII and the corresponding masking function. Run this runbook as the final step of every sub-prod refresh.
✓	Restrict sub-prod database access to developers only (no external access, no PHI-related reporting queries).

RESIDUAL RISK: Manual scripts require discipline and process enforcement. Unlike DMS, there is no automated lineage or audit trail of which columns were masked. Mitigate by documenting the masking runbook and including it in the sub-prod refresh checklist.
 
3.3 Manage User Accounts — Rating: RED — FULLY FIXABLE
All findings in this category are completely fixable using native Oracle password profiles and account management — no additional licensing required. This should be the highest priority remediation given the critical finding status.

Step 1: Immediate Actions (Do Today)
✓	Change default passwords for PEOPLE and PS immediately:
◦	ALTER USER PEOPLE IDENTIFIED BY '<NewStrongPassword>' PASSWORD EXPIRE;
◦	ALTER USER PS     IDENTIFIED BY '<NewStrongPassword>' PASSWORD EXPIRE;
◦	Verify no other accounts have known default passwords: SELECT username, account_status FROM dba_users WHERE account_status = 'OPEN';
✓	Lock or drop the 8 accounts that have never logged in:
◦	-- Identify never-used accounts:
◦	SELECT username, created, last_login FROM dba_users WHERE last_login IS NULL AND account_status = 'OPEN';
◦	ALTER USER <username> ACCOUNT LOCK;  -- lock first, drop after confirming not needed
✓	Force password reset for all accounts with legacy (10g) password hashes:
◦	SELECT username, password_versions FROM dba_users WHERE password_versions LIKE '%10G%';
◦	ALTER USER <username> IDENTIFIED BY '<NewPassword>' PASSWORD EXPIRE;

Step 2: Create Strong Password Profiles
✓	Create separate profiles for application accounts, DBA accounts, and service accounts:
◦	CREATE PROFILE app_user_profile LIMIT
◦	  PASSWORD_LIFE_TIME          90
◦	  PASSWORD_REUSE_TIME         365
◦	  PASSWORD_REUSE_MAX          10
◦	  PASSWORD_VERIFY_FUNCTION    ORA12C_STRONG_VERIFY_FUNCTION
◦	  FAILED_LOGIN_ATTEMPTS       5
◦	  PASSWORD_LOCK_TIME          1/24
◦	  INACTIVE_ACCOUNT_TIME       30
◦	  SESSIONS_PER_USER           5
◦	  IDLE_TIME                   30
◦	  CONNECT_TIME                480;

◦	CREATE PROFILE dba_profile LIMIT
◦	  PASSWORD_LIFE_TIME          60
◦	  PASSWORD_REUSE_TIME         365
◦	  PASSWORD_REUSE_MAX          15
◦	  PASSWORD_VERIFY_FUNCTION    ORA12C_STRONG_VERIFY_FUNCTION
◦	  FAILED_LOGIN_ATTEMPTS       3
◦	  PASSWORD_LOCK_TIME          1/12
◦	  INACTIVE_ACCOUNT_TIME       15
◦	  SESSIONS_PER_USER           3
◦	  IDLE_TIME                   15
◦	  CONNECT_TIME                600;

◦	CREATE PROFILE svc_account_profile LIMIT
◦	  PASSWORD_LIFE_TIME          UNLIMITED
◦	  PASSWORD_VERIFY_FUNCTION    ORA12C_STRONG_VERIFY_FUNCTION
◦	  FAILED_LOGIN_ATTEMPTS       3
◦	  PASSWORD_LOCK_TIME          UNLIMITED
◦	  SESSIONS_PER_USER           10
◦	  IDLE_TIME                   60;

Step 3: Assign Profiles to All Users
✓	Assign profiles to all 50 users (replace DEFAULT for all users):
◦	-- Assign to application accounts:
◦	ALTER USER <app_user> PROFILE app_user_profile;
◦	
◦	-- Assign to DBA accounts:
◦	ALTER USER <dba_user> PROFILE dba_profile;
◦	
◦	-- Verify no users remain on DEFAULT profile:
◦	SELECT username, profile FROM dba_users WHERE profile = 'DEFAULT' AND account_status = 'OPEN';

✓	Ensure SEC_CASE_SENSITIVE_LOGON is TRUE (required for modern password hashing):
◦	ALTER SYSTEM SET SEC_CASE_SENSITIVE_LOGON = TRUE SCOPE = BOTH;
✓	Establish a quarterly user access review process: export dba_users, review with app owners, lock stale accounts.
 
